2014-02-27 00:23:24	technomancy	I'd do a scheme if it had more ram, but the teensy 2 is more limited
2014-02-27 00:23:59	dfj	I have a key which when held locks down any other key until that key his struck and released again...
2014-02-27 00:24:12	dfj	(I usually map it to the capslock key)
2014-02-27 00:24:35	dfj	so - I can hit lock and 'f', and now f will  stay down until I hit f again.
2014-02-27 00:25:11	smrtz|nix	technomancy: Since I'm going with tmk, does that limit the PCBs I can use?
2014-02-27 00:25:15	dfj	I can do this with any or all of the other keys, includign shift if I might want to get something close to teh original function of caps.
2014-02-27 00:25:30	dfj	so - how do I configure that on the timk?
2014-02-27 00:25:37	-->	porcineraccoon (~pilot@64-7-157-204.border8-dynamic.dsl.sentex.ca) has joined #geekhack
2014-02-27 00:25:55	technomancy	dfj: so... a function that keeps having an effect without blocking the other keys might be more difficult considering the teensy can't do concurrency.
2014-02-27 00:26:32	technomancy	smrtz|nix: it means you'll need to use a board that mounts an ATMEGA32U4
2014-02-27 00:26:39	dfj	a simple way to think of it is to imaging a stream of up and down events, like in an OS, or over PS/2 serialization... teh lock key ditches all releases while it is held.
2014-02-27 00:26:45	technomancy	smrtz|nix: I haven't looked into PCBs, but that seems to be by far the most popular chip
